  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What kind of first jobs do neuroscience majors tend to get?",
  "response": "Neuroscience majors often enter a variety of fields due to the interdisciplinary nature of their education. Here are some common first jobs for neuroscience graduates:\n\n1. **Research Assistant/Technician**:\n   - Many neuroscience majors start their careers in academic or industrial research labs. They might work on projects related to brain function, neurodegenerative diseases, or drug development.\n\n2. **Clinical Research Coordinator**:\n   - In this role, neuroscience graduates help manage clinical trials, ensuring that studies are conducted properly and that data is collected accurately.\n\n3. **Pharmaceutical or Biotechnology Sales Representative**:\n   - With a strong understanding of biology and medicine, neuroscience majors can effectively communicate the benefits of new drugs or medical technologies to healthcare professionals.\n\n4. **Medical or Health Services Manager**:\n   - Neuroscience graduates might work in healthcare administration, overseeing the operations of hospitals, clinics, or other healthcare facilities.\n\n5. **Science Writer/Communicator**:\n   - Some neuroscience majors find opportunities in science journalism or public outreach, translating complex scientific concepts into understandable content for the public or other professionals.\n\n6. **Neurodiagnostic Technologist**:\n   - These professionals operate specialized equipment to measure brain and nervous system activity, assisting in the diagnosis of neurological disorders.\n\n7. **Data Analyst**:\n   - Neuroscience graduates with strong quantitative skills may work in data analysis, using their knowledge to interpret data from neurological studies or other health-related research.\n\n8. **Teaching or Education**:\n   - Some may start as teaching assistants or educators in schools, colleges, or science outreach programs, sharing their knowledge of neuroscience.\n\n9. **Mental Health Counselor/Therapist**:\n   - With additional training, neuroscience majors can work in mental health, applying their understanding of brain function to help patients.\n\n10. **Graduate School or Medical School**:\n    - Many neuroscience majors pursue further education, either in a Ph.D. program to become researchers or in medical school to become physicians specializing in neurology, psychiatry, or related fields.\n\nThese are just a few examples, and the actual job opportunities can vary based on individual skills, interests, and additional training or certifications.",
